One oxygen molecule per haemoglobin molecule","Eight oxygen molecules per haemoglobin molecule"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEach haemoglobin molecule contains four haem groups, and each haem group can bind \u003Cstrong\u003Eone oxygen molecule\u003C/strong\u003E. This means a single haemoglobin molecule can carry up to four oxygen molecules when fully saturated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo oxygen molecules per haem group\u003C/strong\u003E - Each haem group has only one binding site for oxygen, making it structurally impossible to bind two molecules.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVariable oxygen binding depending on tissue demand\u003C/strong\u003E - While oxygen affinity changes with local conditions, the maximum binding capacity remains constant at four oxygen molecules.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne oxygen molecule per haemoglobin molecule\u003C/strong\u003E - This greatly underestimates the oxygen-carrying capacity as haemoglobin has four haem groups, each capable of binding oxygen.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEight oxygen molecules per haemoglobin molecule\u003C/strong\u003E - This exceeds the structural capacity of haemoglobin which has only four haem groups.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe binding of oxygen to haemoglobin exhibits positive cooperativity, meaning that binding of one oxygen molecule increases the affinity for subsequent oxygen molecules. This results in the characteristic sigmoidal shape of the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Each haemoglobin molecule can bind up to four oxygen molecules, one at each haem group.","Oxygen binding to haemoglobin is cooperative, meaning binding of one oxygen molecule increases the affinity for subsequent oxygen molecules.","The oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve is sigmoidal due to this cooperative binding."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T22:04:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T22:05:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72512"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i